Challenge Task 1: Install the Metrics Server

First check if it is already running:

kubectl get pods -n kube-system | grep metrics-server

If nothing comes, install it.

For Minikube
minikube addons enable metrics-server
For Kind / kubeadm

Use the official manifest:

kubectl apply -f https://github.com/kubernetes-sigs/metrics-server/releases/latest/download/components.yaml

For local clusters, edit deployment and add:

- --kubelet-insecure-tls

inside container args.

Wait and Verify
sleep 60
kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods -A
Verify Answer

Question: What is the current CPU and memory usage of your node?

Example answer:

Current node usage is 120m CPU and 1.2Gi memory.

Your exact values will depend on your machine.

Challenge Task 2: Explore kubectl top

Run:

kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods -A
kubectl top pods -A --sort-by=cpu
Important Interview Point

kubectl top shows:

actual real-time usage
not requests
not limits

This data comes from Metrics Server every ~15 seconds.

Verify Answer

Question: Which pod is using the most CPU?

Run:

kubectl top pods -A --sort-by=cpu

Top row = highest CPU pod.

Example:

kube-apiserver is currently using the most CPU.

Challenge Task 3: Create Deployment with CPU Requests

Create deployment:

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: php-apache
spec:
  replicas: 1
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: php-apache
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: php-apache
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: php-apache
        image: registry.k8s.io/hpa-example
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80
        resources:
          requests:
            cpu: 200m

Save as php-apache.yaml

Apply:

kubectl apply -f php-apache.yaml
Expose Service
kubectl expose deployment php-apache --port=80
Verify CPU Usage
kubectl top pods

Example answer:

Pod is currently using 25m CPU

Challenge Task 4: Create HPA (Imperative)

Run:

kubectl autoscale deployment php-apache --cpu-percent=50 --min=1 --max=10

Check:

kubectl get hpa
kubectl describe hpa php-apache
Verify TARGETS

Example output:

25%/50%

Meaning:

current CPU usage = 25%
target = 50%
Interview Ready Answer

Question: What does TARGETS show?

TARGETS shows current CPU utilization percentage vs target utilization percentage.

Example: 25%/50%

Challenge Task 5: Generate Load and Watch Autoscaling

Start load generator:

kubectl run load-generator \
  --image=busybox:1.36 \
  --restart=Never \
  -- /bin/sh -c "while true; do wget -q -O- http://php-apache; done"

Watch scaling:

kubectl get hpa php-apache --watch

Also watch replicas:

kubectl get deployment php-apache -w
Expected Behavior

After 1–3 minutes:

CPU > 50%
HPA scales from 1 → 2 → 3 replicas

Possible result:

1 → 4 replicas
Verify Answer

Question: How many replicas did HPA scale to?

Example:

HPA scaled to 4 replicas under load

(Your result may be 2–5 depending on system resources.)

Stop Load
kubectl delete pod load-generator
Challenge Task 6: Create HPA from YAML (Declarative)

Delete old HPA:

kubectl delete hpa php-apache

Create file hpa.yaml

apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
metadata:
  name: php-apache
spec:
  scaleTargetRef:
    apiVersion: apps/v1
    kind: Deployment
    name: php-apache
  minReplicas: 1
  maxReplicas: 10
  metrics:
  - type: Resource
    resource:
      name: cpu
      target:
        type: Utilization
        averageUtilization: 50
  behavior:
    scaleUp:
      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 0
    scaleDown:
      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 300

Apply:

kubectl apply -f hpa.yaml

Verify:

kubectl describe hpa php-apache
Verify Answer

Question: What does the behavior section control?

It controls how quickly pods scale up and scale down.

Example:

immediate scale-up
delayed scale-down (300 sec)

This prevents frequent scaling fluctuations.

Challenge Task 7: Cleanup

Run:

kubectl delete hpa php-apache
kubectl delete service php-apache
kubectl delete deployment php-apache
kubectl delete pod load-generator --ignore-not-found

Keep metrics server installed.
